{"title_page": "General Rani", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistan brothel madam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2011}}\n{{COI|date=December 2014}} \n{{Infobox person\n| name = Akleem Akhtar\n| birth_date = {{circa|1931/1932}}\n| birth_place = [[Gujrat, Pakistan|Gujrat]], [[Punjab, British India|Punjab]], [[British India]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2002|07|1|1931|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]]\n| partner = [[Yahya Khan]] (1967-1971)\n| children = 6\n| relatives = [[Fakhar-e-Alam]] (grandson)<br>[[Adnan Sami]]\n}}\n'''Akleem Akhtar''' (otherwise known as '''Aqleem Akhtar''', '''General Rani'''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paracha |first1=Nadeem F. |title=The fascinating tale of General Rani |url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/tft/the-fascinating-tale-of-general-rani/ |work=Friday Times |date=28 March 2014}}</ref>  or '''Ra'annie Yahya Kahn''') was a [[Pakistani]] [[Procuring (prostitution)|madam]] who ran a [[brothel]]<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\">{{Cite web |url=http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/night-of-the-general/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328044245/http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/night-of-the-general/|archive-date=28 March 2017|title=Night of the General|first=Ayesha|last=Nasir|date=4 May 2002|accessdate=28 March 2017|work=[[Newsline (magazine)|Newsline]]|publisher=Newsline Publications}} </ref> in [[Rawalpindi]] in 1960s. She became the [[Mistress (lover)|mistress]] of her client and future President [[Yahya Khan]] and was known as country's most powerful woman during his regime.\n\n==Early life==\nAkhtar was born in [[Gujrat city|Gujrat]] in [[Punjab, British India]] in 1931 or 1932.<ref name=\"DawnDeath\">{{Cite news |url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/07/02/top18.htm |publisher=Dawn.com |date=2 July 2002 |title=\u2018Gen Rani\u2019 dies of cancer |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> She married a Police Officer Moiz je, inhabitant of North Karachi (sector 11-L), much older than herself.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/> When on holiday in [[Murree]], Akhtar removed her naqab in defiance of her husband and told him she was going to live her own life.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nThe dramatic conclusion of Akhtar's marriage was a turning point in her life. In a May 2002 interview with Newsline, Akhtar stated:\n\n<blockquote>\u201cI was determined to beat men at their own game. Since my husband was in the police, I had been observing men in positions of power throughout my married life and I had realised that all men in positions of power needed a vent and the vent they require the most is a bedmate provided through a reliable agency. The higher a man\u2019s position, the greater his demand.\u201d<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/></blockquote>\n\nThus Akhtar adopted a motto of \u2018miyan ki juti miyan ke sir\u2019 which means to 'beat men at their own game'{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} and started a prostitution business.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nAkhtar had not acquired formal skills or qualifications to support an independent career but she had come to know many rich and powerful men through frequenting clubs with her former husband.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} She met General Yahya Kan via these means and a relationship between them developed.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\n==Relation to Yahya Khan==\nDue to Akhtar's close association with [[Yahya Khan]] and power she exercised due to the connection she was known as General Rani (''General's Queen''). She is said to have lovingly called Yahya Kahn Agha Jan. Akhtar held no official position, but she was given \"full protocol\".{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} She denied she was Yahya Khan's \"mistress\" and claimed that they were merely friends.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAkhtar and her husband had six children together in Akhtar's early years.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\nAkhtar is the grandmother of leading pop star [[Fakhre Alam]].<ref name=\"PkHeraldFakhar\">{{Cite web |url=http://pakistanherald.com/Profile/Fakhar-e-Alam-797 |work=Pakistan Herald |publisher=Gibralter Information Technologies |title=Fakhar-e-Alam: Actor, VJ and Singer}}</ref> A maternal niece of hers, Naureen, was the mother of singer [[Adnan Sami]].<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\n==Death==\nIn May 2002, Pakistani media reported that Akhtar was suffering from breast cancer that has metastasised in her liver and kidney.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nAkhtar died of cancer on 1 July 2002, aged 73 (approx), at Sheikh Zayed Hospital in [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"DawnDeath\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rani, General}}\n[[Category:1930s births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Gujrat District]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani brothel owners and madams]]\n[[Category:Pakistani sex workers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistan brothel madam}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2011}}\n{{COI|date=December 2014}} \n{{Infobox person\n| name = Akleem Akhtar\n| birth_date = {{circa|1931/1932}}\n| birth_place = [[Gujrat, Pakistan|Gujrat]], [[Punjab, British India|Punjab]], [[British India]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2002|07|1|1931|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Lahore]], [[Pakistan]]\n| partner = [[Yahya Khan]] (1967-1971)\n| children = 6\n| relatives = [[Fakhar-e-Alam]] (grandson)<br>[[Adnan Sami]]\n}}\n'''Akleem Akhtar''' (otherwise known as '''Aqleem Akhtar''', '''General Rani'''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paracha |first1=Nadeem F. |title=The fascinating tale of General Rani |url=http://www.thefridaytimes.com/tft/the-fascinating-tale-of-general-rani/ |work=Friday Times |date=28 March 2014}}</ref>  or '''Ra'annie Yahya Kahn''') was a [[Pakistani]] [[Procuring (prostitution)|madam]] who ran a [[brothel]]<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\">{{Cite web |url=http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/night-of-the-general/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328044245/http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/night-of-the-general/|archive-date=28 March 2017|title=Night of the General|first=Ayesha|last=Nasir|date=4 May 2002|accessdate=28 March 2017|work=[[Newsline (magazine)|Newsline]]|publisher=Newsline Publications}} </ref> in [[Rawalpindi]] in 1960s. She became the [[Mistress (lover)|mistress]] of her client and future President [[Yahya Khan]] and was known as country\u2019s most powerful woman during his regime.\n\n==Early life==\nAkhtar was born in [[Gujrat city|Gujrat]] in [[Punjab, British India]] in 1931 or 1932.<ref name=\"DawnDeath\">{{Cite news |url=http://archives.dawn.com/2002/07/02/top18.htm |publisher=Dawn.com |date=2 July 2002 |title=\u2018Gen Rani\u2019 dies of cancer |accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> She married a Police Officer Moiz je, inhabitant of North Karachi (sector 11-L), much older than herself.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/> When on holiday in [[Murree]], Akhtar removed her naqab in defiance of her husband and told him she was going to live her own life.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nThe dramatic conclusion of Akhtar's marriage was a turning point in her life. In a May 2002 interview with Newsline, Akhtar stated:\n\n<blockquote>\u201cI was determined to beat men at their own game. Since my husband was in the police, I had been observing men in positions of power throughout my married life and I had realised that all men in positions of power needed a vent and the vent they require the most is a bedmate provided through a reliable agency. The higher a man\u2019s position, the greater his demand.\u201d<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/></blockquote>\n\nThus Akhtar adopted a motto of \u2018miyan ki juti miyan ke sir\u2019 which means to 'beat men at their own game'{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} and started a prostitution business.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nAkhtar had not acquired formal skills or qualifications to support an independent career but she had come to know many rich and powerful men through frequenting clubs with her former husband.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} She met General Yahya Kan via these means and a relationship between them developed.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\n==Relation to Yahya Khan==\nDue to Akhtar's close association with [[Yahya Khan]] and power she exercised due to the connection she was known as General Rani (''General's Queen''). She is said to have lovingly called Yahya Kahn Agha Jan. Akhtar held no official position, but she was given \"full protocol\".{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} She denied she was Yahya Khan's \"mistress\" and claimed that they were merely friends.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nAkhtar and her husband had six children together in Akhtar's early years.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\nAkhtar is the grandmother of leading pop star [[Fakhre Alam]].<ref name=\"PkHeraldFakhar\">{{Cite web |url=http://pakistanherald.com/Profile/Fakhar-e-Alam-797 |work=Pakistan Herald |publisher=Gibralter Information Technologies |title=Fakhar-e-Alam: Actor, VJ and Singer}}</ref> A maternal niece of hers, Naureen, was the mother of singer [[Adnan Sami]].<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\n==Death==\nIn May 2002, Pakistani media reported that Akhtar was suffering from breast cancer that has metastasised in her liver and kidney.<ref name=\"NightOfGeneral\"/>\n\nAkhtar died of cancer on 1 July 2002, aged 73 (approx), at Sheikh Zayed Hospital in [[Lahore]].<ref name=\"DawnDeath\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rani, General}}\n[[Category:1930s births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Gujrat District]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani brothel owners and madams]]\n[[Category:Pakistani sex workers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo 