{"title_page": "Will You (Hazel O'Connor song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Will You\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Hazel O'Connor]]\n| album      = [[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]\n| B-side     = \"Sons And Lovers\" <ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web|url= https://www.discogs.com/Hazel-OConnor-Will-You/master/189944\n|title=Hazel O'Connor \u2013 Will You |website=Discogs |accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| released   = 1980\n| format     = \n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[New wave]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=04|s=49}}\n| label      = [[A&M Records]]\n| writer     = [[Hazel O'Connor]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = \n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Will You'''\" is a song by British singer-songwrier [[Hazel O'Connor]] taken from her debut album, the soundtrack to [[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]. It reached no. 8 on the UK charts in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/18656/hazel-oconnor/\n|title=Hazel O'Connor - Official Charts|publisher=official charts.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Will You\" is the only track on the album that doesn't appear in the film. O'Connor revealed in her autobiography that she wrote the song a long time before the film was made. As a ballad,\"Will You\" stands out as a departure from her usual style.<ref>{{citeweb|URL=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/hazel-oconnor/will-you\n|title = Hazel O'Connor Will You|publisher = songfacts.com|accessdate = 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Will You\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Hazel O'Connor]]\n| album      = [[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]\n| B-side     = \"Sons And Lovers\" <ref name=\"Discogs\">{{cite web|url= https://www.discogs.com/Hazel-OConnor-Will-You/master/189944\n|title=Hazel O'Connor \u2013 Will You |website=Discogs |accessdate= 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n| released   = 1980\n| format     = \n| recorded   = \n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[New Wave]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=04|s=49}}\n| label      = [[A&M Records]]\n| writer     = [[Hazel O'Connor]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = \n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Will You'''\" is a song by British singer-songwrier [[Hazel O'Connor]] taken from her debut album, the soundtrack to [[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]. It reached no. 8 on the UK charts in 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/18656/hazel-oconnor/\n|title=Hazel O'Connor - Official Charts|publisher=official charts.com|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Will You\" is the only track on the album that doesn't appear in the film. O'Connor revealed in her autobiography that she wrote the song a long time before the film was made. As a ballad,\"Will You\" stands out as a departure from her usual style.<ref>{{citeweb|URL=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/hazel-oconnor/will-you\n|title = Hazel O'Connor Will You|publisher = songfacts.com|accessdate = 2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n", "name_user": "Starcheerspeaksnewslostwars", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_You_(Hazel_O%27Connor_song)"}
{"title_page": "Real Betis", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| nickname = ''Los Verdiblancos'' (The Green-and-Whites)<br> ''Verderones'' (Big Greens)<br>''B\u00e9ticos''<br> ''Heliopolitanos'' (Heliopolitans)<br>''Lobos'' (Wolves)<br> '' El Glorioso'' (The Glorious)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.estadiodeportivo.com/betis.php?id=32602&pg=26 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101234900/http://www.estadiodeportivo.com/betis.php?id=32602 |archivedate=2012-11-01 }}</ref>\n| ground = [[Estadio Benito Villamar\u00edn]]\n| capacity = 60,720<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realbetisbalompie.es/en/noticias/last-news/9366/ramon-alarcon-va-a-quedar-un-estadio-benito-villamarin-del-siglo-XXI|title=New features for Benito Villamar\u00edn Stadium|website=www.realbetisbalompie.es|language=en|access-date=2017-06-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804174056/http://www.realbetisbalompie.es/en/noticias/last-news/9366/ramon-alarcon-va-a-quedar-un-estadio-benito-villamarin-del-siglo-XXI|archivedate=2017-08-04}}</ref>\n| pattern_la1 = _betis1920h\n| pattern_b1 = _betis1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _betis1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _betis1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _betis1920h\n| leftarm1 = 137F22\n| body1 = 137F22\n| rightarm1 = 137F22\n| shorts1 = FFFFFF\n| socks1 = 137F22\n| pattern_la2 = _betis1920a\n| pattern_b2 = _betis1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _betis1920a\n| pattern_so2 = _betis1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = _betis1920a\n| leftarm2 = 000000\n| body2 = 000000\n| rightarm2 = 000000\n| shorts2 = 000000\n| socks2 = 000000\n| pattern_la3 = _betis1920t\n| pattern_b3 = _betis1920t\n| pattern_ra3 = _betis1920t\n| pattern_so3 = _betis1920t\n| pattern_sh3 = _betis1920t\n| leftarm3 = FCA7C7\n| body3 = FCA7C7\n| rightarm3 = FCA7C7\n| shorts3 = FCA7C7\n| socks3 = FCA7C7\n| clubname = Real Betis\n| image = real betis logo.svg\n| image_size = 230px\n| fullname = Real Betis Balompi\u00e9, [[Sociedad An\u00f3nima Deportiva|S.A.D.]]\n| short name = RBB, Betis\n| founded = {{Start date and age|12 September 1907}} as ''Sevilla Balompi\u00e9''\n| chairman = \u00c1ngel Haro\n| chrtitle = President\n| manager = [[Rubi_(footballer)|Rubi]]\n| mgrtitle = Head coach\n| league = [[La Liga]]\n| season = [[2018\u201319 La Liga|2018\u201319]]\n| position = La Liga, 10th\n| current = 2019\u201320 Real Betis season\n| website = http://www.realbetisbalompie.es/\n}}\n{{Real Betis sections}}\n'''Real Betis Balompi\u00e9''', [[Sociedad An\u00f3nima Deportiva|S.A.D.]], more commonly referred to as '''Real Betis''' ({{IPA-es|re\u02c8al \u02c8\u03b2etis|pron}}) or just '''Betis''', is a football club based in [[Seville]], in the autonomous community of [[Andalusia]]. Founded on 12 September 1907, it plays in [[La Liga]], having won the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] in the [[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2014\u201315 season]]. It holds home games at [[Estadio Benito Villamar\u00edn]] in the south of the city with 60,720-seat capacity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/laliga-top-10-stadiums-power-13974425|title=We ranked the top 10 stadium in La Liga - with a surprise No.1|last=Jones|first=Rich|date=2019-02-09|website=mirror|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref>\n\nReal Betis won the league title in [[1934\u201335 La Liga|1935]] and the [[Copa del Rey]] in [[1976-77 Copa del Rey|1977]] and [[2004-05 Copa del Rey|2005]]. Given the club's tumultuous history and many relegations, its motto is ''\u00a1Viva el Betis manque (aunque) pierda!'' (\"Long live Betis even when they lose!\").<ref name=\"BETIS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=109997.html|title=Real Betis, 100 years of passion|publisher=FIFA.com|date=18 January 2007|accessdate=26 April 2011}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe name \"Betis\" is derived from ''[[Hispania Baetica|Baetis]]'', the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] name for the [[Guadalquivir]] river which passes through Seville and which the Roman province there was named after. ''Real'' was added in 1914 after the club received patronage from [[King of Spain|King]] [[Alfonso XIII of Spain|Alfonso XIII]].\n\n===Foundation===\n[[File:Alineaci\u00f3n del Real Betis Balompie, 1913..jpg|thumb|right|Real Betis, 25 December 1913]]\n[[File:Monumento betis 002.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Betis' [[1934-35 La Liga]] title is commemorated by this sculpture in Seville]]\nBetis' city rivals [[Sevilla FC]] were the first club in Sevilla, founded in October 1905, while a second club, ''Sevilla Balompi\u00e9'' were established in September 1907. \"''Balompi\u00e9''\" translates literally as \"football\", as opposed to the most commonly adopted anglicised version, \"''f\u00fatbol''\". Balompi\u00e9 was founded by students from the local Polytechnic Academy, and were in operation for two years before being officially recognised (in 1909); despite this 1907 remains the official foundation date of the club.\n\nFollowing an internal split from Sevilla FC, another club was formed, Betis Football Club. In 1914, they merged with Sevilla Balompi\u00e9. The club received its royal patronage in the same year, and therefore adopted the name '''Real Betis Balompi\u00e9'''. Fans continued to refer to the club as ''Balompi\u00e9'' and were themselves known as ''Los Balompedistas'' until the 1930s, when ''Betis'' and the adjective ''B\u00e9ticos'' became common terminology when discussing the club and its followers.\n\nReal Betis wear a green and white kit now but played in all blue jerseys and white shorts, for no other reason than the easy availability of such plain colors.{{cn|date=April 2019}} But keen to take advantage of his ongoing relationships made in Scotland, Manuel Ramos Asensio \u2013 one of the founders and captain \u2013 was able to make contact with Celtic and secure the same fabric used to make the famous hoops for his own club.{{cn|date=April 2019}} There is, however, no mention of Celtic or Scotland in the history of Betis on the club's official website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realbetisbalompie.es/club/la-historia/|title=La historia - Real Betis Balompi\u00e9|website=www.realbetisbalompie.es}}</ref>  After successfully taking receipt of the necessary material, Manuel was keen to make a statement with the team's new jerseys, by inverting the green and white lines into vertical ones to make the strips - something quite unheard of at the time in Spain. It was a move that ultimately gave birth to the Betis we see today.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n===1930s: promotion, championship and relegation===\nDuring the [[Spanish Second Republic]] (1931\u20131939), royal patronage of all organisations was nullified, and thus the club was known as '''Betis Balompi\u00e9''' until after the [[Spanish Civil War]] when it would revert to the full name. The club reached the [[Copa del Rey|Copa del Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica]] final for the first time on 21 June 1931, when it lost 3\u20131 to [[Athletic Bilbao]] in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tabless/spancup1931.html|title=Spain - Cup 1931|website=rsssf.com|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> Betis marked their 25th anniversary year by winning their first [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] title in [[1931\u201332 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1932]], finishing two points ahead of [[Real Oviedo|Oviedo FC]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rsssf.com/tabless/spanhist2839.html|title=Spain, Final Tables 1928-1939|website=rsssf.com|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> thus becoming the first club from [[Andalusia]] to play in [[La Liga]].\n\nUnder the guidance of Irish coach [[Patrick O'Connell (Irish footballer)|Patrick O'Connell]] on 28 April 1935 [[1934\u201335 La Liga|Betis won the La Liga]], to date their only top division title. They topped the table by a single point over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Madrid FC]]. A year later Betis went down to [[1935\u201336 La Liga|seventh]]. This was due to the dismantling of the championship-winning team because of the club's poor economic situation and the arrival of the Civil War, meaning that just 15 months after lifting the league title only two players who won in 1935 were left: Peral and Saro. No official league was held during the Civil War between 1936 and 1939, until its resumption for the 1939\u201340 season and the first year back highlighted Betis' decline as exactly five years after winning the title the club was [[1939\u201340 La Liga|relegated]].\n\n===Darkest period===\nDespite a brief [[1942\u201343 La Liga|return to the top division]] which lasted only one season, the club continued to decline and in 1947 the worst fears were reached when they were relegated to [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]. Many fans see the ten years they spent in the category as key to the \"identity\" and \"soul\" of the club. During this time, Betis earned a reputation for filling its stadium and having a massive support at away matches, known as the \"Green March\".\n\nWhen the side returned to the second level in 1954, it gained the distinction of being the only club in Spain to have won all three major divisions' titles. Much of the credit for guiding Betis through this dark period and back into the ''Segunda'' lies with chairman Manuel Ruiz Rodr\u00edguez.\n\n===Benito Villamar\u00edn===\nIn 1955, Manuel Ruiz Rodr\u00edguez stepped down from running the club believing he could not offer further economic growth, he was replaced by Betis most famous former president, Benito Villamar\u00edn. During his reign Betis returned to the top division in [[1958\u201359 La Liga|1958\u201359]] and finished in third place in [[1963\u201364 La Liga|1964]]. His purchase of the [[Estadio Benito Villamar\u00edn|Estadio Heli\u00f3polis]] in 1961 is seen as a key point in the history of the club \u2013 the grounds were called the ''Estadio Benito Villamar\u00edn'' until 1997. In 1965, Villamar\u00edn stepped down from his position after ten years at the helm of the club.\n\nJust one year after Villamar\u00edn's departure, the club would again be relegated to division two, then rising and falling almost consecutively until consolidating their place in the top level in [[1974\u201375 La Liga|1974\u201375]].\n\n===First Copa del Rey Title and European Qualification===\n[[File:Manolo Diaz en el Betis 1 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Real Betis 1974/75]]\nOn 25 June 1977, Betis played Athletic Bilbao at the [[Vicente Calder\u00f3n Stadium]] in the [[1976\u201377 Copa del Rey#Final|Copa del Rey final]]. The match finished 2\u20132, with Betis winning 8\u20137 after a staggering 21 [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] taken. This rounded off a solid season in which the club [[1976\u201377 La Liga|finished fifth in the league]].\n\nAfter that triumph, Betis [[1977\u201378 European Cup Winners' Cup|competed]] in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]: after knocking out [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] 3\u20132 on aggregate in the first round, the side reached the quarter-finals, where they lost to [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]]. Despite their strong performance in [[UEFA|Europe]], the team [[1977\u201378 La Liga|suffered league relegation]].\n\nThe following year, Betis returned to the top flight and ushered in a period of \"good times\" for the club, with the next three seasons seeing three top-six finishes, as well as [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] qualification in [[1981\u201382 La Liga|1982]] and [[1983\u201384 La Liga|1984]].\n\nDuring the summer of 1982, the Benito Villamar\u00edn hosted two matches as part of the [[1982 FIFA World Cup]], and also witnessed the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]]'s famous [[Spain vs Malta 1984 UEFA European Football Championship qualifying match|12\u20131 hammering]] of [[Malta national football team|Malta]] in order to [[UEFA Euro 1984 qualifying|qualify]] for [[UEFA Euro 1984]].\n\n===Economic crisis and Manuel Ruiz de Lopera===\nIn 1992, Betis found itself subject to new league rules and regulations due to its restructuring as an autonomous sporting group (SAD), requiring the club to come up with 1,200 million [[Spanish peseta|pesetas]], roughly double that of all the first and second division teams, despite being in level two at the time.\n\nIn just three months, the fans raised 400&nbsp;million pesetas with then vice-president [[Manuel Ruiz de Lopera]] stepping in to provide an economic guarantee while himself becoming majority shareholder as the team narrowly avoided relegation.\n\nOn 11 September 1994 Real Betis played its 1,000th game in La Liga.\n\n===Serra Ferrer success===\nAfter another three seasons in the second division, with the club managed by [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]], Betis [[1993\u201394 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|returned to the top flight]] for the [[1994\u201395 La Liga|1994\u201395 season]], subsequently achieving a final third position, thus [[1995\u201396 UEFA Cup|qualifying to the UEFA Cup]].[[File:Camiseta aniversario betis 001.jpg|thumb|right|Betis' shirts in 2007 bore an emblem for their centenary]]In the European campaign, Betis knocked out [[Fenerbah\u00e7e S.K. (football)|Fenerbah\u00e7e]] (4\u20131 on aggregate) and [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]] (4\u20131) before losing to [[1996 UEFA Cup Final|defeated finalists]] [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] (3\u20132). In 1997, 20 years after winning the trophy for the first time, the club returned to the final of the Copa del Rey \u2013 again held in Madrid, although this time at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] \u2013 [[1997 Copa del Rey Final|losing 2\u20133]] against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] after [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]].\n\nIncidentally, ''Bar\u00e7a'' was the club Serra Ferrer would leave Betis for that summer, to be replaced by former player [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]]. Aragon\u00e9s would only last [[1997\u201398 La Liga|one season]] with the club, leading the side to the eighth position and to [[1997\u201398 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|the quarter-finals in the Cup Winners' Cup]], where they would lose 2\u20135 on aggregate to eventual winners [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].\n\nAragon\u00e9s was followed by the controversial reign of [[Javier Clemente]], who spat on a fan and implied Andalusia was \"another country!\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}} The team slipped down the table, [[1998\u201399 La Liga|finishing 11th]] and [[1998\u201399 UEFA Cup|being knocked out of the UEFA Cup]] by [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in the third round. For the next couple of seasons, Betis went through numerous managers, a relegation and a promotion, after which the team [[2001\u201302 La Liga|finished sixth in the league]] with [[Juande Ramos]] at the helm.\n\nRamos was gone after just one season, however, being replaced by former Cup Winners' Cup-winning manager [[V\u00edctor Fern\u00e1ndez]]. He led the team to [[2002\u201303 La Liga|eighth]] and [[2003\u201304 La Liga|ninth]] in the league and the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|third round of the 2002\u201303 UEFA Cup]], being knocked out by [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]] (1\u20132 on aggregate), during his two-year reign.\n\nFor 2004, Fern\u00e1ndez was replaced by the returning Serra Ferrer, who guided the team to the [[2004\u201305 La Liga|fourth position in the top flight]]. They also returned to the Vicente Calder\u00f3n on 11 June 2005 for the [[2004\u201305 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey final]], lifting the trophy for only the second time after an extra-time winner by youth graduate [[Dani (footballer, born 1981)|Dani]] in a [[2005 Copa del Rey Final|2\u20131 win]] against [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]].\n\nThe league finish meant Betis became the first Andalucian team to compete in the [[UEFA Champions League]], and it reached [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|the group stage]] after disposing of [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the last qualifying round (3\u20132 on aggregate). Drawn in Group G, and in spite of a 1\u20130 home win against Chelsea, the club eventually finished third, being \"demoted\" to the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], where it would be ousted in the [[round of 16]] by defeated [[FC Steaua Bucure\u0219ti|Steaua Bucure\u0219ti]] (0\u20130 away draw, 0\u20133 home loss).\n\n===Centenary celebrations===\n[[File:Rgordillo.jpg|thumb|[[Rafael Gordillo]], Betis player and president]]\nBetis celebrated their [[Century|centenary]] year in 2007. The festivities included a special match against Milan, the [[2007 UEFA Champions League Final|reigning European Champions]], on 9 August, with the hosts winning 1\u20130 thanks to a [[Mark Gonz\u00e1lez]] [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] early in the second half. Seven days later, the club won the [[Ram\u00f3n de Carranza Trophy]] held in neighbouring [[C\u00e1diz]], beating [[Real Zaragoza]] on penalties in the final, having defeated Real Madrid in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realbetisbalompie.es/noticias/comunicados.html?id=3693|title=Todos los partidos de la pretemporada 2007\u201308|trans-title=All the matches in the 2007\u201308 preseason|publisher=Real Betis|language=Spanish|date=17 August 2007|accessdate=26 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091230090139/http://realbetisbalompie.es/noticias/comunicados.html?id=3693|archivedate=30 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nSurrounding the celebration, it was a time of great change in terms of the playing and technical teams, with eight new signings replacing 14 departures. During the two seasons ([[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]] and [[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]]) that encompassed the centenary year, Betis had four different managers. During the latter campaign, the club was the 37th-best followed team in Europe regarding average attendances.\n\n===Segunda Divisi\u00f3n===\nAfter many years of staving off relegation, Betis' [[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u201309 season]] culminated with a 1\u20131 draw against [[Real Valladolid]] at home. With this outcome, the club finished 18th in the table and consequently was relegated to the second division.\n\nOn 15 June 2009, over 65,000 ''Beticos'', including icons such as [[Rafael Gordillo]], Del Sol, [[Hip\u00f3lito Rinc\u00f3n]], [[Julio Carde\u00f1osa]] and others, joined the protest march in Sevilla with the slogan \"''15-J Yo Voy Betis''\" to let the majority owner Ruiz de Lopera know that it was time to put his 54% share of the club on the market for someone, some entity or the Betis supporters to buy those shares and remove Lopera from the day-to-day operations of the club.\n\nDespite the protests, no upper management changes were made during [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the season]], which would ultimately see Betis fail to gain promotion back to the top level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2009/06/03/andalucia_sevilla/1244011067.html|title=Lopera sigue mudo y ultras lo amenazan: 'Vende o muere'|trans-title=Lopera still says nothing and is threatened by ''ultras'': 'Sell or die'|publisher=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|date=3 June 2009|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Lopera court action and sale===\nSeville judge Mercedes Alaya was investigating links between Betis and other Ruiz de Lopera-owned businesses, leading to him being formally charged with fraud. On 7 July 2010, one week before the start of preliminary court proceedings, Lopera sold 94% of the shares that he owned (51% of Betis total shares) to Bitton Sport, fronted by Luis Oliver, for the surprisingly low figure of [[Euro|\u20ac]]16&nbsp;million, leaving Lopera with only minor shares; Oliver had already reportedly taken two football clubs, [[Cartagena FC|Cartagena]] and [[Xerez CD|Xerez]], to the brink of bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/10/27/futbol/equipos/betis/1288188407.html|title=Oliver: \"Ni los nazis hac\u00edan lo que hace esta loca\"|trans-title=Oliver: \"Not even nazis did what this crazy woman does\"|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=Spanish|date=27 October 2010|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBefore the sale could be officially sanctioned, however, Ayala froze Lopera shareholdings. Left with nothing, despite putting down a \u20ac1&nbsp;million deposit, Oliver hastily bought a nominal number of shares from a third party and was voted onto the board of directors by the existing members (all former cohorts of Lopera), allowing him to carry on running the club. In response to this, the judge appointed well-respected former Betis, Real Madrid and Spain national team legend [[Rafael Gordillo]] to administrate Lopera's shares to ensure Lopera was not still running the club and that decisions made were for the benefit of the club not individual board members.<ref>[http://eldesmarque.es/betis/33746-la-venta-se-cierra-en-16-anos-a-pagar-en-5-anos La venta se cierra en 16 millones a pagar en 5 a\u00f1os (Sold for 16 millions to be paid in 5 years)]; El Desmarque, 7 July 2010 {{in lang|es}}</ref>[[File:Tifo europeo en un derbi - Estadio Benito Villamarin.jpg|thumb|[[Estadio Benito Villamar\u00edn]]]]\n\n===La Liga return===\nAgain under [[Pepe Mel]], Betis started [[2011\u201312 La Liga|2011\u201312]] with four wins in as many games, with [[Rub\u00e9n Castro]] retaining his goal scoring form from [[2010\u201311 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the previous season]], where he scored 27 goals. Betis finished 13th in their first season since returning to La Liga.\n\nIn the [[2012\u201313 La Liga|2012\u201313 season]], Betis finished seventh in La Liga and qualified for the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League]], the first European qualification for the club since the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|2005\u201306 Champions League]]. This European campaign ended in the quarter-finals after losing on penalties to local rivals Sevilla.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spot-on Sevilla get the better of Betis|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2014/matches/round=2000471/match=2012664/index.html|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=[[UEFA]]|date=20 March 2014}}</ref>  Betis were relegated from La Liga with three games still to play in the [[2013\u201314 La Liga|2013\u201314 season]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Ronaldo brace sends Real second, Betis relegated|url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/nationalleagues/nationalleague=spain-liga-2000000037/news/newsid/232/462/5/|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=[[FIFA]]|date=26 April 2014}}</ref> but [[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|returned immediately as champions]] with two games to spare.<ref>{{cite news|title=Real Betis win promotion to Primera Division after Alcorcon victory|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11827/9864193/real-betis-win-promotion-to-primera-division|accessdate=26 May 2015|work=Sky Sports|date=25 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Seville derby==\n[[File:Regatsasevillabetis2009.JPG|thumb|right|Betis and their city rival [[Sevilla FC]] also compete in an annual rowing race on the [[Guadalquivir]] river]]\n{{See also|El derbi Sevillano}}\nBetis have a long-standing rivalry with city neighbours [[Sevilla FC]].<ref name=\"BETIS\"/> The two have met 114 times in official competition, with Sevilla holding a 45% win ratio over Betis (31%).\n\nThe first match between the two clubs took place on 8 February 1915, with Sevilla winning 4\u20133. The match was not completed, as high tensions led an aggressive crowd to invade the pitch, forcing the [[Referee (association football)|referee]] to abandon the match.\n\nIn 1916, the first ''Copa Andaluc\u00eda'' was held, this being the first official derby of the Sevilla area. Of the 17 runnings of the cup, Sevilla were victorious 14 times, to Betis' one sole conquest; this included a 22\u20130 routing after the latter sent their youth team, in 1918.\n\nThe first time the teams met in league, in ''Segunda'', happened in 1928\u201329, with both teams winning their home matches (3\u20130 and 2\u20131). They played for the first time in the Spanish top division during the 1934\u201335 season, with a 0\u20133 home defeat for Sevilla and a 2\u20132 draw at Betis, with the latter winning the national championship.\n\nOn 17 January 1943, Betis lost 5\u20130 at Sevilla, eventually being relegated. In the first game held at the [[Ram\u00f3n S\u00e1nchez Pizju\u00e1n Stadium]], on 21 September 1958, the ''Verdiblancos'' won it 4\u20132.\n\nIn later years, several matches were also marred by violence, including: a security guard attacked by a Sevilla fan with a crutch (that he did not require to walk), Betis [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Antonio Prats Cervera|Toni Prats]] being attacked and Sevilla manager Juande Ramos being struck by a bottle of water;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/mar/01/europeanfootball.sport2|title=This was no isolated incident|publisher=The Guardian|date=1 March 2007|accessdate=26 April 2011}}</ref> the latter incident led to the [[2006\u201307 Copa del Rey|2007 Copa del Rey match]] being suspended, being played out three weeks later in [[Getafe]] with no spectators.\n\nOn 7 February 2009, Betis won 2\u20131 at the Pizju\u00e1n, but was eventually relegated from the top flight, while Sevilla finished in third position. \n\nOn November 9, 2019 more than 10,000 Betis fans visited the team training before the last derby in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/betis/2019/11/09/5dc70f8722601d300b8b45a9.html|title=M\u00e1s de 10.000 b\u00e9ticos arropan a su equipo en el \u00faltimo entrenamiento antes del derbi|date=2019-11-09|website=Marca.com|language=es|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> \n\n===Statistics===\n\n====La Liga====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Team !! Wins !! Home !! Away\n|-\n| '''Betis''' ||    28    ||    18    ||    10\n|-\n| '''Sevilla''' || 38 || 26 || 12\n|}\nPlayed 84, with 18 draws.\n\n* ''Betis have scored 101 goals against their rivals, but have conceded 118.''\n\n====Segunda Divisi\u00f3n====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Team !! Wins !! Home !! Away\n|-\n| '''Betis''' ||